player.seasonOutlook: Griffin has missed at least two games in three of the past four seasons and has never finished a season better than 24th in fantasy points. The 2013 sixth-round pick has managed 37 catches over the past two seasons and has never eclipsed two touchdowns in a single season. The 29-year-old is currently a free agent.

Harmon surprisingly fell to the sixth round of April's draft, which is where he was selected by the Redskins. Harmon is a big (6-foot-2, 221 pounds), physical perimeter receiver with good hands, ball skills and blocking ability. The N.C. State product is not particularly speedy (4.64 40-yard dash) or quick and was dreadful after the catch last season, posting a prospect-worst 3.1 RAC. Of course, he still caught 81 passes while working as both a vertical threat and reliable possession target. Harmon has some upside despite his plummet on draft weekend, and Washington's shaky depth chart provides him plenty of opportunity for rookie-season playing time. Keep him on your watch list.

Houston selected Warring in the third round of April's draft. This after the team drafted tight ends Jordan Akins and Jordan Thomas in 2018, which obviously means this depth chart is a bit crowded. Warring is a massive specimen at 6-foot-5, 252 pounds. The San Diego State product is a capable blocker and his combination of size, speed (4.67 40-yard dash), quickness, route-running ability and athleticism offers him big-time upside as a receiver. The small-handed former basketball star has struggled with drops (seven on 85 FBS targets) and post-catch production (prospect-worse 2.8 RAC last season), but makes sense as a developmental flier. He's likely to be buried on the depth chart in 2019.

A converted wide receiver, Seals-Jones generated some hype last season when called on to play an every-down role for Arizona. It didn't go well for the 2017 undrafted free agent. Despite handling a generous 15 percent target share, Seals-Jones finished 29th in fantasy points, and his best weekly finish was 10th. His 50 percent catch rate and 5.0 YPT both ranked dead last at the position, though in his defense, a position-high 25 percent of balls thrown his way were off-target. The 24-year-old could see a resurrection in Kliff Kingsbury's new offense, but he'll first need to beat out Charles Clay and Maxx Williams. He's not worth drafting.

Ridley was selected by the Bears in the fourth round of April's draft. Calvin's brother is 6-foot-1, 199 pounds and profiles as a physical possession receiver. Ridley is a quality route runner with reliable hands and was productive near the goal line at Georgia. The former Bulldog lacks top-end speed (4.58 40-yard dash) and post-catch production (ugly 3.4 RAC last season), but he should make his name in the short-to-intermediate area, while adding value as a run blocker. He does not have a clear path to snaps in 2019 with Allen Robinson, Taylor Gabriel, Anthony Miller and perhaps Cordarrelle Patterson higher on the depth chart. Ridley is only worth a look in dynasty.

Heuerman made some noise with a random 10-catch game in Week 9 last season, but otherwise failed to post a weekly fantasy finish better than 17th. The 2015 third-round pick has yet to appear in more than 14 games in a regular season and struggled badly with efficiency in a role as a short-area target last season. The 26-year-old is a long shot for fantasy value after Denver drafted Noah Fant in the first round of April's draft.

The Bengals selected Sample in the second round of April's draft. Sample (6-foot-5, 255 pounds) is a good blocker and competent pass catcher who has drawn Jack Doyle comps. He has a good combination of speed, hands and ball skills, which were highlighted by him hauling in all but one of his 26 catchable targets last season, as well as a solid combine showing (including a 4.71 40-yard dash). Like most rookie tight ends, expect Sample to play a situational role as a rookie. He has little fantasy value with Tyler Eifert and C.J. Uzomah ahead of him on the depth chart.
